{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170847/1946040401/0195.xml":{"full_text":"NEW YORK BANK\nOPTIMISTIC ABOUT\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nNational City Hopes Long\nCoal Strike Doesn't Build\nNew Barrier to Peacetime\nTrade\nWull Street orrespolHlenee\nOf The Bcpabilean\nNew York, April I\u2014Stock, that\nwere active today continued highly\nselective both new highs and lows\nfor the. year occurring in specialties.\nPivotals were firm but quiet. On the\nnews of a 100 per cent stock divi\nde.\u2019d, Wyandotte Worsted made a\nquick advance of more than five\npoints. American Woolen and other\ntextiles were strong. Liquor and air\ntransportation shares were on the\nsoft side. There was no real selling\npraaaure, however, in anj\nthe market, which again acted as\nthough it wanted to go up if some\nof the overhanging uncertainties dis\nappeared.\nDespite the coal strike and a num\nber of other unsettled labor dis\nputes, the industrial outlook appeared\nbrighter during the month just\nended, the National City bank here\nsays in its April letter that on the\nwhole the strike wave appears to\nbe receding: that wage increases\nhave gone the rounds of most ma\n.ior industries, and price advances to\ncover, or partially cover, the in\ncreased costs have been made in\nsome important areas.\nMany Troubles Faced\n\"Difficulties of the industries in\nthe past five or six months\u2014un\navoidable where due to physical\nproblems of reconversion\u2014have been\nincreased and complicated beyond\nall necessity by labor 1 roubles and\nrestrictive price policy,\" the bank\nletter says. \"First was the problem\nof finding enough workers, ami in\nmany eases of getting efficient work\nfrom those on the pay roll. On the\nheels of labor shortages came wage\ndemands, strikes, and government in\ntervention to establish a pattern of\nwage increases, leading in turn to\nrising costs and squeezes against the\nprice ceilings. Confusion spread, and\nwas topped by uncertainty as to\nwhether or when the needed price\nrelief would bo obtained.\n\"These confusions and uncertainties\ngtill persist in many places. They are\nInevitable when the government as\nsumes direction of business, to the\nextent of making the wage and price\ndecisions on which the life of busi\nness depends. It is too much to hope\nthat they can be wholly eliminated.\nStatements by union leaders that re\ncent wage gains are \u2018merely a down\npayment\" suggest that the end of\nthe present wave of increases may;\nrun into the beginning of the next:\nwave. This will be all the more likely I\nif Mr Lewis succeeds in obtaining\nincreases for the coal miners which\ngo beyond the. pattern established in\nsteel and other industries. Price ceil\nings continue repressive in many lines\nI and will be repressive in one area\nI or another as long as they last.\"\nRecent actions by the Office of\nPrice Administration on price relief\napplications \"have seemed to reflect\na more flexible and realistic atti\ntude,\" it is pointed out, \"and some\nprogress is being made toward work\ning out the necessary new\u2019 balance of\nwages, costs and prices on which the\nindustries can get to work. The la\nbor supply is more abundant. The\ntest of the situation is whether pro\nduction is increasing, and with all\nthe difficulties there are signs that\nthe upward trend has been made. The\ncoal strike. If prolonged more than\ntw\u2019o or three weeks, will cause an\nother general setback, but it the ca\nlamity of a long coal shutdown can\nbe averted the prospect is that a\nlarger volume of goods will be com\ning on the markets.\u201d\nSteel production recovered during\nMarch io above the prestrike level, it\nis pointed out; the automobile indus\ntry is at last ready to go ahead and\nexpects to lift its output tn its present\ncapacity by midsummer; textile mills\nare obtaining more workers and have\nbeen encouraged by liberalization of\nprice ceilings and production is trend\ning upward; more people are at work\non leather and paper production than\nthere were a year ago.\nThe federal reserve, index of indus\ntrial production, which measures the\naggregate output of all the industries,\ndeclined in January and February\nreaching in the last named month a\nlow of 154 of the 1935-39 average\ntaken at 100, it. is recalled, due to\nstrikes and the effect of strikes \u201cFor\nMarch.\" it is added, \"with recovery in\nsteel production, the index is certain\nto show a. good rebound.\u201d\nAll developments since the turn of\nthe year, it is stated,\" have empha\nsized the insatiable demand for goods\nand the ability of buyers to pay for\nall they can get. Income payments\nto individuals have been sustained.\nI despite cutbacks in war production\nI and strikes, to a degree which few\nI thought possible. Retail trade has ex-;\nceeded the most optimistic expecta-j\ntfons.\" R. L. BARNUM.\nPAL CUTLERY STRIKERS\nREJECT NEW PROPOSAL\nHolyoke, April I\u2014The striking em\nployes of the Pal Cutlery company\nthis afternoon rejected the proposal\nbrought to the negotiating commit\ntee on Saturday by Norton Mailman,\nrelative of two of the coowners of the\ncompany, that the workers return to\ntheir work pending revelation of \u2018a\nnew plan\u201d not yet detailed. The. 750\nworkers have been on strike since\nlast Monday, seeking increased base\npay. holiday allowances, health and\naccident insurance and vacation pay-\nD. J. Oates, international vice\npresident of the Metal Polishers'\nunion A FL, of which the Pal union\nan' affiliate, and William Malone,\nbusiness agent, expect that Robert\nCosgrove of Springfield. United Stales\nconciliator, will arrange further con\nferences in an effort to get the two\nparties closer together.\nOne of the oft-repeated grievances\nthe strikers have is that absentee;\nownership makes negotiations diffi\ncult. They have demanded that one\nnr more of the coowners, of New\nYork, come here to grant or reject\ndemands or designate someone of the\nrepresentatives of management at the\nlocal plant with authority to act. The\nworkers refer Io the experiences of\nlast year when negotiations extended\nover a period of four months.\nBANK STATEMENTS\nChase National Hank\nNew York. April 2 (API--Chase\nNational hank reported today a de\ncline in deposits on March 30 to\n$5 140.087.000 from 15.742.18f1.00(1 al\nthe end of December. This compared\nwith $4.497.5(W;000 at the end of\nMarch. 1945.\nTotal resources at the end of ihe\nlatest quarter amounted to $6,498,511.-\n414. compared with $6,092,601,000 at\nthe year-end and $4,822,301,000 a year\nago.\nHoldings of United States Sp'W 1\nment securities declined to $2,960.27\n000 from $3,078,103,000 at the end *'f\nI the preceding quarter hut were still\nahead of |2.\u20197\u00bb 151 \"'MI a year earlier\nL Net e^rninss so first qua\u00ab*ter\nof 1946 amounted I 88 cents a Share,\nFIN ANC IA t\ncompared with 31.02 In the like 1915\nquarter.\nNational City Bank\nNational City bank of New York\nreported a decline in assets as of\nMarch 31 to 35,248,215,883 from 35.-\n431,372,599 nt the end of December\nDeposits dropped to 34.948,852,510\nfrom 85,113,122.214. Holdings of\nUnited States government obligation,\ncontracted to $2,577,056,578 from\n773,488,219 at the cud of the preced\ning quarter.\nEarnings of National City and City\nBank Farmers Trust Co., stock of\nwhich Is beneficially owned by NCR\nshareholders, totaled 37.878,058, equal\nto $1.27 a. share, In the first quarter\nof 1916, against $7,046,450. or sl.ll a\nshare, in the comparable 1915 quat ler\n4-DOOR CHEVROLET\nRETAIL CEILING UP\nOPA Allows $43 Boost Over\n1942 Price \u2018Due Entirely\nto Engineering Changes,\nImprovements\u2019\nWashington. March 29 (AP)\nThe retail ceiling price for 12,000 new\nChevrolet four-door sedans will be\n$43 more than the price for 1942\nmodels, OPA. announced today.\nThese ears, produced before the\nGeneral Motors strike, were given\na retail celling of $876, as compared\nwith the 1942 price of $833.\nThe agency said last November that\nretail prices for all new General Mo\ntors cars\u2014Chevrolet, Pontiac, Olds\nmobile. Buick and Cadillac\u2014would\naverage about 2.5 per cent below\nJanuary. 1942. levels.\nOPA. said the $43 increase is \"due\nentirely to engineering changes and\nimprovements.\u201d\nMage Boost Not Considered\nThe. new price, the first fixed for\nany of the General Motors cars, does\nnot take into consideration the wage\nincrease of 18' 2 cents hourly granted\nrecently by the corporation, OPA\nsaid.\nOPA does not regard increases for\ndesign changes and engineering im\nprovements as an increase in basic\nretail prices, \"rhe agency said that\nin the case of the Chevrolet four\ndoor sedan these modifications in\nclude styling changes in body, in\nterior appointments, grill and bump\ners. improved cooling and braking\nsystems, a new\u2019 steering assembly and\nchanges in the engine.\nCeiling prices for factory sales to\ndealers are the retail price less a dis\ncount of 21.7 per cent to socalled\ndirect dealers and 19.9 per cent to\nassociate dealers m carload lots.\nThe new retail price of $876 does\nno\", include federal excise, taxes, trans\nportation. or preparation and han\ndling charges.\nMINERS\u2019 WALKOUT\nCHILLS EXCHANGE\nExpected Event Dampens\nEnthusiasm and Leaders\nDrop \u2014Oils Buoyed by OPA\nAnnouncement\nNew York. April 1 (AT) \u2014The\nwalkout of 400.000 soft coal miners,\nwhile fully expected, seemed to chill\nbullish enthusiasm in today\u2019s stock\nmarket and, while assorted favoriH'S\nmanaged to overcome the handicap,\nleaders generally took the downward\ntrail.\nEarnings, dividends and the urge\nto invest Mlfe cash still provided buy\ning incentives.\nBids for utilities developed when\nthe supreme co(irt handed down the\nlong-waited decision upholding the\n\"death sentence\u201d clause of the hold\ning company act. Although the ma\njority failed to follow through, most\nretained advances of fractions to a\npoint or so. Demand here was cred\nited to the thought that assets of\naffiliates, not already distributed, now\nwould be prorated to stockholders.\nAnnouncement of the OPA that the\nrecent crude ceiling lift would take\neffect immediately buoyed some of\nthe oils*.\nDealings were relatively sluggish\nfollowing a fairly active opening,\nlosses running to better than 3 points\npredominated at the close although\nmany extreme declines wore reduced.\nTransfers of 1.050.000 shares com\npared with 1.220.000 Friday.\nThe Associated Press 60-stock com\nposite was off .2 of a point at 77.6.\nOf 910 issues appearing, 452 fell and\n307 rose.\nIn the curb Chesebrough common,\nan odd-lot issue, jumped 5\u20194 on sales\nof 75 shares in response to a split\nup proposal. Childs Co. preferred\nadded 6^ on 160 shares. Hearns De\npartment Stores was up 2%. Turn\nover in this market was 5 40,000 shares\nversus 470.000 in the preceding full\nsession.\nN. H. RAILROAD GIVEN\nPERMISSION TO PAY\nCourt OKs Payment of\n$9,041,134 in Interest On\nBonds and Debentures\nOne Request Opposed\nNew Haven. Ct.. March 29 \u2014(AP)\u2014\nPetitions of the trustees ot the New\nYork, New Haven Hartford railroad\nto pay $9,041,134 Interest on bonds and\ndebentures were approved by Judge\nCarrol! C. Hincks in United States\ndistrict court here today.\nOpposition to one petition involving\na payment item of $7,918,819 was\nvoiced by Joseph M. Hartfield of New\nYork, representing the Bankers Trust\nCo. This payment item includes the\nsemiannual instalments which became\ndue between May 1 and October 1 of\n1943 and between November 1 of 1913\nand tile following April on securities\nof the railroad\u2019s first and refunding\nI mortgage. the principal of which\nI amounts to $165,861,050.\nThe other payments which the\n'trustees sought permission to pay\nwhen they fall due this year Include\n$70,175 on May 1 on the Housatonic\nRailroad Co. 5 per cent consolidated\nmortgage gold bonds outstanding In\nthe sum of $2,819,000; $300,000 on May\n1 on New York. New Haven. Hartford.\nHarlem River. Portchester 4 per cent\nfirst mortgage 50-year gold bonds\noutstanding in the amount of $15,-\n000.000; the $50,000 due also on May 1\non the Naugatuck Railroad Co.'s first\nmortgage 4 per cent 50-year gold\nbonds outstanding in the principal ot\n$2,500,000: S7OOO due on June 1 on\nDanbury and Norwalk Railroad Co.\n4 per cent 50-year first mortgage\n[gold bonds in the amount of $350,000:\nS4OOO coming up June 1 on New\nHaven and Northampton Co. 4 ner\ncent 50-year refunding consolidated\nI mortgage gold bonds at present out\nistanding at $2,400,000; the July 1\ninterest of $387,500 on the New Eng\nland Railroad Co. 4 per cent and 5\nI per cent 50-year consolidated mort\nigage gold bonds with $10,000,000 nut\ni standing in the 4 per cent bonds and\ni $7,500,000 in the 5 per cent bonds: and\nithe $259,340 due July 1 on Central\n1 New England Railroad Co. I per cent\n50-year first mortgage gild bonds out\nstanding at $12,967,000.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY. AP*U 4,1946\nSale of Stocks\nNow York Slock exchange .1,040.H1M1\nNew Sork I urh exellnoge 510,1100\nBoston Stock exchange 16,256\nSales in 100 s High Low Clone Chg.\nA\n2 ACF Brill Mot 15% 13% 15% r\n4 Arnie Sil 36% 36% 36% 1\n5 A Janis Exp 21'i 21% 2[%\n3 Addressog-M 37% 3\" 37\nI Admiral c 16% >V%\n17 Air Reduction 58 '\u00bbj% 58 +2%\n7 Aldens Jnr 42 41 42 -1\n2'\u00bb Maska Jun 9 8% 8%\n26 Alleg Corp 6% 6% d%\n7 Do pt 57% 57 57\n4 AI leg Lud S 41% 43% 13%\n1 Allen Ind 22'x 22% 22%\n2 Alll.d Kid 25 25 25\nI Allied Mills 3\u00bb% 34% 34%\nII Allied HtlS 57 56% 56%-\n11 Allis Ch Mfg 52% 61% 52% F\n5 Amal Leather 8% 8% S%\n3 Amerada Pet ...165 182% 165 1\n3Am AR Ch Del 41% 41% 41%\n(I Am Airlines 89% 88 88%\u2014\nIf) Am Bank Note 40% 40 40% f\nI Do pf 81% 81% R)% 1\n4Am Brake Shoe 55% 51 55% 3%\n19 Am Cable Bad 11% 13% 14%\n5 Am Can 04% 93% 93%\n.10 Do pf 207 207 207\n0 Am Car Edy