w York Grain Market\nNew York. April 2- Api\u2014Cash wheat\nsi ron^: Nn. 2 dark northern spring \u00abIU\nN, Y.. 2 02% nominal; No. 1 northern Mum-,\ntoha FOR N. V., 8\u2019\nt'orn strong: No. 2 yellow CIF N. Y.\nRyp steailj No 2 American FOR N. T.\narloisi, 2.6<\u2019%: No. 2 western CIF, N Y-.\ninis strong. No. while CIF N Y\nRatie> strong; No. 2 domestic CIF N. Y..\n1...\nFINANCIAL\nANGRY SENATORS\nTACK FARM RIDER\nONTO WAGE BILL\nPass Higher Farm Prices\nAmendment to Minimize\nWage Bill 30 Minutes\nAfter Truman Veto Threat\nWashington. March 29\u2014(AP) In\nan angry uprising against the admin\nistration. the Renate today tacked a\n1 higher-farm-pricea amendment to the\nindustrial minimum wage bill only 30\ni minutefl after President Truman had\nwarned he would veto the proposition.\nThe vote was 43 to 31 in favor of\nthe amendment whic h the adrninis\ni tration\u2019g economic high command had\nI labeled as inflationary but which\nfarm-minded senators declared was\nonly fair to the nation s agriculture.\nTrvMsa FhhbAmmi 'eto\nMs.mrity leader Harkiey told\ncolleaguw* late in the day that F'res\n(dent Truman had authorized him to\ntell them he would be \u201ccompelled\u201d to\nveto the wage bill if it came to him\nbearing the farm rider.\nHalf an hour later, 24 Democrat*,\nincluding most of the southern mem\nbers, okayed the farm proposal. They\nwere joined by 19 Republicans.\nLined up against the amendment\nwere 21 of Mr Truman's party, nine\nRepublicans, and La Follette (Prog-\nWis).\nBefore the vote, Senator Russel!\n(D-Ga). a leader in the light for\nthe amendment, bitterly deplored the\nWhite House intervention as \"coer\ncion and intimidation.\u201d He said the\nI\u2018resident had \"no right to come into\nCongress with a threat to veto.\"\nThe Senate's decision, coupled with\nthe White House warning, left ex\ntremely uncertain the fate of the bill\ndesigned to raise minimum wages in\nindustry.\nThe Senate recessed until Monday\nio think it over, but there seemed no\nchance the farm price action could,\nor would be reversed.\nRevises Parity Formnia\nThe amendment, sponsored by Sen\nator Russell (D-Ga), would revise thej\nj farm crop parity formula by includ-1\njing th#' cost of farm labor in the\ncomputation.\nParity is a price designed tn give\nrhe farmer buying power equivalent'\nto that, in a fa vorable base period. It;\nis important in day-to-day price lev-\nels because it is the basis for the\nj present crop support program and is\none of the bases for food price ceil\nings.\nPrice Administrator Paul Porter\nhas declared that the new formula!\nwould raise America s grocery bill by I\n$4,000,000,000 a year. Stabilization Ad- i\nministrator Chester Bowles estimated\nth? increase at $4,500,000,000.\nFarm state senators, however, de\nfended the plan on the ground that\nif industrial wages are to be raised,\nthe farmers\u2019 income should be boost\ned too.\nThe bill to which the Senate nailed\nrhe amendment would raise rhe min\nimunj statutory wage from its present;\nj level of 40 cents an hour to 65 cents:\nI immediately, and eventually to 75\ncents.\nStrong support, however, already\nhas been demonstrated for an alter-;\nJ nate plan which would make the ini\nj tiai increase to 55 cents, with a new\nfloor of 60 cents to take effect 18\nmonths later.\nThe wage bill is on the first stage\n\u0964of its parliamentary journex Once\nJ cleared by the Senate, it goes to the\nI House. That body, farm senators\ni pointed out. twice in recent years\nhad approved legislation identical\nwith the Russell amendment.\nEARNINGS STATEMENTS\nHudson Motor (ar Co.\nDetroit. March 29\u2014(A P)\u2014Hudson\nMotor Car Co. today reported a 1945\nnet income of $673,248, nearly 6ft\nper cent below rhe figure for the\nprevious year.\nIn his annual report. A. E. Barit,\npresident and general manager, said\nearnings per share in 1945 were\n42 cents compared with $1.07 in\n1944. when net income totalled sl.-\nj 698.634.\nBarit reported that Hu